adding label and title on bar graph

In[]:

y=[85,82,67,56]

plt.ylabel("popularity",fontsize=17)

plt.title("language surveys",fontsize=20)

plt.bar(x,y)
plt.show()

changing color or graph width

In[]:
x=["python","java","c++","c"]
y=[85,82,67,56]

plt.xlabel("language",fontsize=17)
plt.ylabel("popularity",fontsize=17)

plt.title("language surveys",fontsize=20)

c=['red','b','yellow',"violet"]

plt.bar(x,y,width=0.5,color=c)
plt.show()

some parameters
align: it moves the xlabel to "center" or "edge"
edgecolor: it color the boundary of plot by color given
linewidth: it decides the width line of boundary
linestyle: it change the style of boundary from default
alpha: it decides the color contrast of plots vary from 0-1

In[]:
x=["python","java","c++","c"]
y=[85,82,67,56]

plt.xlabel("language",fontsize=17)
plt.ylabel("popularity",fontsize=17)

plt.title("language surveys",fontsize=20)

c=['red','b','yellow',"violet"]

plt.bar(x,y,width=0.5,color=c,align="center",edgecolor="black",linewidth='3',
        linestyle='-',alpha=0.6)
plt.show()

label parameter can be used to put label within plot sheet and can be used to by plt.legend() key

In[]:
x=["python","java","c++","c"]
y=[85,82,67,56]

plt.xlabel("language",fontsize=17)
plt.ylabel("popularity",fontsize=17)

plt.title("language surveys",fontsize=20)

c=['red','b','yellow',"violet"]

plt.bar(x,y,width=0.5,color=c,align="center",edgecolor="black",linewidth='3',
        linestyle='-',alpha=0.6,label="survey")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

plotting two bar at single sheet

In[]:
import numpy as np

x=["python","java","c++","c"]
y=[85,82,67,56]
z=[95,78,54,45]

width=0.2
p=np.arange(len(x))



plt.xlabel("language",fontsize=17)
plt.ylabel("popularity",fontsize=17)
plt.title("language surveys",fontsize=20)



plt.bar(x,y,width,color="red",label="survey2021")
plt.bar(x,z,width,color="violet",label="survey2024")

plt.legend()
plt.show()

in above program there is an issue that the one plot is on another if we want to plot sidewise with each category we use a for loop method as p1

In[]:
x=["python","java","c++","c"]
y=[85,82,67,56]
z=[95,78,54,45]

width=0.2
p=np.arange(len(x))
p1=[i+width for i in p]




plt.xlabel("language",fontsize=17)
plt.ylabel("popularity",fontsize=17)
plt.title("language surveys",fontsize=20)



plt.bar(p,y,width,color="red",label="survey2021")
plt.bar(p1,z,width,color="violet",label="survey2024")

plt.legend()
plt.show()

there is one more problem we can see that in lanaguage ther s some numbers instead of name of programmig so we use "plt.xticks()" or two align name in center we use p+width/2

rotation of text can also be done by rotation=

In[]:
x=["python","java","c++","c"]
y=[85,82,67,56]
z=[95,78,54,45]

width=0.2
p=np.arange(len(x))
p1=[i+width for i in p]




plt.xlabel("language",fontsize=17)
plt.ylabel("popularity",fontsize=17)
plt.title("language surveys",fontsize=20)



plt.bar(p,y,width,color="red",label="survey2021")
plt.bar(p1,z,width,color="violet",label="survey2024")

plt.xticks(p+width/2,x,rotation=20)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

if we want to plot horizontal bar we use plt.barh() instead of plt.bar()

In[]:
y=["python","java","c++","c"]
x=[85,82,67,56]
z=[95,78,54,45]

width=0.2
p=np.arange(len(y))
p1=[i+width for i in p]




plt.ylabel("language",fontsize=17)
plt.xlabel("popularity",fontsize=17)
plt.title("language surveys",fontsize=20)



plt.barh(p,x,width,color="red",label="survey2021")
plt.barh(p1,z,width,color="violet",label="survey2024")


plt.yticks(p+width/2,y,rotation=20)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

How to use scatter plot all concept

In[]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x=[10,20,30,40,50,70,90]
y=[40,62,73,84,95,116,227]

c=["r",'b','g','y',"r","b","g"]
sizes=[50,90,100,500,600,900,1100]

plt.scatter(x,y,color=c,s=sizes,marker="*",edgecolor="black")

plt.title("power production",fontsize=18)
plt.xlabel("KWatts",fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel("frequency",fontsize=15)

plt.show()

cmap: used to show the color bondary level such as accent,binary,viridis etc.

In[]:
x=[10,20,30,40,50,70,90]
y=[40,62,73,84,95,116,227]

sizes=[50,90,100,500,600,800,850]
colors=[10,49,70,68,50,82,99]

plt.scatter(x,y,c=colors,s=sizes,cmap="binary")
t=plt.colorbar()
t.set_label("colorbar",fontsize=15)

plt.title("power production",fontsize=18)
plt.xlabel("KWatts",fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel("frequency",fontsize=15)


plt.show()

for two scatter plot in one graph

In[]:
x=[10,20,30,40,50,70,90]
y=[40,62,73,84,95,116,227]
z=[60,70,54,42,25,90,156]

sizes=[50,90,100,500,600,800,850]
colors=[10,49,70,68,50,82,99]

plt.scatter(x,y,c=colors,s=sizes,cmap="binary")
plt.scatter(x,z,color="r",s=sizes,alpha=0.4)

t=plt.colorbar()
t.set_label("colorbar",fontsize=15)

plt.title("power production",fontsize=18)
plt.xlabel("KWatts",fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel("frequency",fontsize=15)


plt.show()

pie chart all concepts

In[]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x=[10,20,30,40]
y=["c","c++","java","pyhton"]

plt.pie(x,labels=y)

plt.show()

explode parameter it clears the visual of the pie part by removong from the whole piechart

In[]:
x=[10,20,30,40]
y=["c","c++","java","pyhton"]
ex=[0.4,0.0,0.0,0.0]

plt.pie(x,labels=y,explode=ex)

plt.show()

to show the percentage in the piegraph by using autopct="%0.1f%%"

In[]:
x=[10,20,30,40]
y=["c","c++","java","python"]
ex=[0.4,0.0,0.0,0.0]
c=["r",'b','g','y']

plt.pie(x,labels=y,explode=ex,colors=c,autopct="%0.1f%%",shadow=True,
        radius=1.0,labeldistance=1.1,startangle=180,
        textprops={"fontsize":18},wedgeprops={"linewidth":3,"edgecolor":"black"},
        )
plt.title("PROGRAMMING LANG.",fontsize=18)

plt.legend(loc=1,fontsize=8)
plt.show()

multi pie chart

In[]:
x=[10,20,30,40]
y=["c","c++","java","python"]
x1=[20,40,10,30]

c=["r","m","g",'y']

plt.pie(x,labels=y,radius=1.75,autopct="%0.1f%%",
        textprops={"fontsize":18},
        wedgeprops={"linewidth":3,"edgecolor":"black"})
plt.pie(x1,radius=0.75,colors=c,autopct="%0.1f%%",
        wedgeprops={"linewidth":1,"edgecolor":"blue"})


plt.show()

HOW TO USE STEM PLOT

"linefmt=" is use to change the stem plot line format

In[]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x=[1,2,3,4,5,6]
y=[2,5,4,6,7,2]

plt.stem(x,y,linefmt=":")

plt.show()

markerfmt parameter use to change the shape or color of the dot

In[]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x=[1,2,3,4,5,6]
y=[2,5,4,6,7,2]

plt.stem(x,y,linefmt=":",markerfmt="go")

plt.show()

bottom parameter can be used to read tyhe from required point like below we used to read our data from 2

In[]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x=[1,2,3,4,5,6]
y=[2,5,4,6,7,2]

plt.stem(x,y,linefmt=":",markerfmt="go",bottom=2)

plt.show()
In[]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x=[1,2,3,4,5,6]
y=[2,5,4,6,7,2]

plt.stem(x,y,linefmt=":",markerfmt="go",bottom=0,basefmt="m",
         label="python")


plt.legend()
plt.show()

use_line_collection=false is used to change th line color with base color

In[]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x=[1,2,3,4,5,6]
y=[2,5,4,6,7,2]

plt.stem(x,y,linefmt=":",markerfmt="go",
         bottom=0,basefmt="m",label="python",orientation="horizontal")


plt.legend()
plt.show()

ALL ABOUT BOX PLOT AND WHISKER PLOT

In[]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x=[10,20,30,40,50,60,70]


plt.boxplot(x)



plt.show()

notch parameter change the shape of box plot to notch

In[]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x=[10,20,30,40,50,60,70]


plt.boxplot(x,notch=True)



plt.show()

vert= parameter can change the box plot to vertically and width= parameter can used to increase or decrease the width of box plot

adding label we have to give data as a list

In[]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x=[10,20,30,40,50,60,70]


plt.boxplot(x,tick_labels=["python"],patch_artist=True)



plt.show()

showmeans parameter can be used to show means pointer between the line as a triangle

In[]:
x=[10,20,30,40,50,60,70]


plt.boxplot(x,tick_labels=["python"],showmeans=True)



plt.show()

the outler (a circle above the plot) is shown it means the data is out of range

In[]:
x=[10,20,30,40,50,60,70,200]


plt.boxplot(x,tick_labels=["python"],showmeans=True)



plt.show()

to join whisk to outler we use whis parameter

In[]:
x=[10,20,30,40,50,60,70,200]


plt.boxplot(x,tick_labels=["python"],showmeans=True,whis=4)



plt.show()
In[]:
x=[10,20,30,40,50,60,70,200]


plt.boxplot(x,tick_labels=["python"],showmeans=True,
            sym="m+",boxprops=dict(color="blue"),capprops=dict(color="r"),
           )



plt.show()

plot multiple box plot

HOW TO CREATE STEP PLOT

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

y=[3,2,1,4,2]

plt.step(x,y)

plt.title("python")

plt.ylabel("y-axis")



plt.grid()
plt.show()

we use markdown function as to mark the point of labeled data given

x=[1,2,3,4,5]

ALL ABOUT FILL_BETWEEN PLOT

In[]:
x=[1,2,3,4,5]
y=[1,2,3,4,5]

plt.plot(x,y,color="r")
plt.title("python")
plt.xlabel("x-axis")
plt.ylabel("y-axis")

plt.fill_between(x,y,color="g")



plt.show()
In[]:
x=[1,2,3,4,5]
y=[1,2,3,4,5]

plt.plot(x,y,color="r")
plt.title("python")
plt.xlabel("x-axis")
plt.ylabel("y-axis")

plt.fill_between(x=[2,4],y1=2,y2=4,color="g")



plt.show()

USE OF WHERE ARGUMENT FOR DESIRED ARE TO BE FILL BETWEEN

we use numpy to convert into array and to perform where operations due to comparison works only on numpy arrays

In[]:
import numpy as np
x=np.array([1,2,3,4,5])
y=np.array([1,2,3,4,5])

plt.plot(x,y,color="r")
plt.title("python")
plt.xlabel("x-axis")
plt.ylabel("y-axis")

plt.fill_between(x,y,color="g",where=(x>=2)&(x<=4),alpha=0.5)



plt.show()

HOW TO PLOT SUBPLOT

BY USING SUBPLOT PARAMETER WE CAN GET DIFFERENT OR SAME TYPE OF PLOT AT SAME PAGE OR AXIS WHICH DEPENDS ON POSITION OF INDEXING

In[]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x=[1,2,3,4]
y=[1,2,3,4]
plt.subplot(2,2,1)
plt.plot(x,y,color="r")

plt.subplot(2,2,2)
plt.pie([1],colors="r")

x1=[10,20,30,40]
plt.subplot(2,2,3)
plt.pie(x)


x2=['a','s','o','r']
y2=[10,20,30,40]
plt.subplot(2,2,4)
plt.bar(x2,y2)


plt.show()

HOW TO SAVE EXTERNALLY MATPLOTLIB GRAPH BY COMMAND WHICH WERE CREATED

we use plt.savefig parameter to save by default as png of plots and for more clearity we use dpi

In[]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x=["python","java","c++","c"]
y=[85,82,67,56]

plt.xlabel("language",fontsize=17)
plt.ylabel("popularity",fontsize=17)

plt.title("language surveys",fontsize=20)

c=['red','b','yellow',"violet"]

plt.bar(x,y,width=0.5,color=c,align="center",edgecolor="black",linewidth='3',
        linestyle='-',alpha=0.6)


plt.savefig("bargraph.jpg",dpi=2000,facecolor="y",bbox_inches="tight")



plt.show()

working with text while plotting graph

In[]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x=[1,2,3,4,5]
y=[3,1,5,6,2]

plt.plot(x,y)

plt.title("Growth of Python",fontsize=18)
plt.xlabel("DAYS",fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel("python",fontsize=15)

plt.show()

for adding a text at a particular point of plot we use plt.text()

In[]:
x=[1,2,3,4,5]
y=[3,1,5,6,2]

plt.plot(x,y)

plt.title("Growth of Python",fontsize=18)
plt.xlabel("DAYS",fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel("python",fontsize=15)

plt.text(3,5,"profit",fontsize=12,style="italic",
         bbox={"facecolor":"green"})



plt.show()

we use plt.anotate() parameter to point an arrow with text to any position on axis

In[]:
x=[1,2,3,4,5]
y=[3,1,5,6,2]

plt.plot(x,y)

plt.title("Growth of Python",fontsize=18)
plt.xlabel("DAYS",fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel("python",fontsize=15)

plt.text(3,5,"profit",fontsize=12,style="italic",
         bbox={"facecolor":"green"})

plt.annotate("loss",xy=(2,1),xytext=(3.5,3),
             arrowprops=dict(facecolor="red",shrink=100))

plt.axis([0,8,0,7])


plt.legend(["margin"],loc=1,facecolor="yellow",edgecolor="black",framealpha=0.5)
plt.show()
